<div style="font-family:Agency FB; background:#000000; color:#FFFFFF; border:3px solid #C4C4C4; box-shadow: 0px 0px 7px #000000; padding:5px 10px; margin:1em; text-align:left;font-size:20px">

<center><font size=5><span style="color: #008080; text-shadow: 0px 0px 5px #003153">Water was never my strong suit, even in the Frontrooms.</span></font></center>



<center><font size=5><span style="color: #008080; text-shadow: 0px 0px 5px #003153">All my life, I remember my friends and family splashing around in pools, playing in the waves at the beach, and riding huge, thrilling waterslides.</span></font></center>



<center><font size=5><span style="color: #008080; text-shadow: 0px 0px 5px #003153">But I never did.</span></font></center>



<center><font size=5><span style="color: #008080; text-shadow: 0px 0px 5px #003153">Every time, someone would ask why I'm feeling down, why I did not join in on the fun like the rest of them.</span></font></center>



<center><font size=5><span style="color: #008080; text-shadow: 0px 0px 5px #003153">I would always give excuses, never telling anyone that I was deathly afraid of water.</span></font></center>



<center><font size=5><span style="color: #008080; text-shadow: 0px 0px 5px #003153">But fears always have a way of being discovered by others.</span></font></center>



<center><font size=5><span style="color: #008080; text-shadow: 0px 0px 5px #003153">One fateful day, a video of one of my freakouts to entering a hot tub was published to the internet.</span></font></center>



<center><font size=5><span style="color: #008080; text-shadow: 0px 0px 5px #003153">Everything changed after that. I was the laughingstock of the whole school, everybody called me "salt girl", "scaredy cat", and others. I lost a whole bunch of "friends" who immediately joined in on the crowd and began to bully me.</span></font></center>



<center><font size=5><span style="color: #008080; text-shadow: 0px 0px 5px #003153">I slowly began to distance myself from others, hid out from public events, and kept to myself within the school's bathrooms. I developed depression, crippling insecurity, and my self confidence was in the toilet.</span></font></center>



<center><font size=5><span style="color: #008080; text-shadow: 0px 0px 5px #003153">I still remember, on the exact moment I entered the Backrooms, I wished for the ground to open up, for me to disappear from this world, and for everyone to forget that I even exist.</span></font></center>



<center><font size=5><span style="color: #008080; text-shadow: 0px 0px 5px #003153">And my wish seemed to have come true, as in that next moment, the only thing I felt was a sensation of falling, before landing with a damp thud.</span></font></center>



<center><font size=5><span style="color: #008080; text-shadow: 0px 0px 5px #003153">At that time, I considered the Backrooms a blessing, even with hordes of [[Entity List|incomprehensible horrors]] lurking around every corner. All the people I met, more specifically came across, did not care about me, or even make fun of me, they were just trying to survive like I was.</span></font></center>



<center><font size=5><span style="color: #008080; text-shadow: 0px 0px 5px #003153">During my journey I assembled a close-nit group of friends, who cared about me as a person, and developed serious survival strategies and resource management skills.</span></font></center>



<center><font size=5><span style="color: #008080; text-shadow: 0px 0px 5px #003153">Even with the danger of the Backrooms, my fear of water never faded away.</span></font></center>



<center><font size=5><span style="color: #008080; text-shadow: 0px 0px 5px #003153">Something as simple as a puddle would make me jump out of my skin, especially after a near-death encounter with the [[Hydrolitis Plague]] near the beginning of my journey.</span></font></center>



<center><font size=5><span style="color: #008080; text-shadow: 0px 0px 5px #003153">Places like [[Level 7]] or [[Level 37]] became my worst nightmares, despite the latter being known for safety and comfort.</span></font></center>


<center><font size=5><span style="color: #008080; text-shadow: 0px 0px 5px #003153">But that all changed one day, as I was afflicted by the absolute embodiment of my greatest fears.</span></font></center>







{{Underline|ADD8E6}}
{{Underline|ADD8E6}}
<font size=4px>
'''Phenomenon 42''', more commonly known as "Sensory Deprivation", "Isolation", or simply "Stasis", is a rare phenomenon that manifests randomly to individuals experiencing severe stress or anxiety. Initially, '''Phenomenon 42''' manifests subtly, with subjects forming an unnatural fascination with water or environments containing water, no matter if the subject possess water related phobias, such as hydrophobia or thalassophobia. This fascination becomes more extreme as time passes, with individuals regularly consuming and immersing themselves in water and waterlike substances, such as [[Object 1|Almond Water]]. 

After approximately 2 weeks, all exits out of one's current level will be blocked off and will be redirected to an anomalous underwater expanse known as '''Phenomenon 42A'''. The expanse is indefinitely deep, with no ocean floor and no surface, though sunlight streams in from an unknown source. Upon entry, all senses will be dampened except for sight and smell, and all video cameras will cease working. Despite being surrounded by water, one is able to breathe within '''Phenomenon 42A''' via an unknown fashion. After entry, subjects will remain in '''Phenomenon 42A''' for around 24 hours to 5 days, after which an unknown vacuum force will pull one out of the expanse and transport them to a random aquatic themed level, where one will regain all senses, and all technology will begin to function again.

Individuals who have experienced '''Phenomenon 42''' have reported a wide range of personality shifts, ranging from differing outlooks on life to reduced fears, an ability to control themselves, and an increase of happiness. Subjects have also reported their life flashing before their eyes, with forgotten details of specific life events or lost memories able to be discovered again. Many have often described '''Phenomenon 42''' as a therapeutic experience, as the silent underwater isolation provides a well renowned break from the horrors of the Backrooms.

Typically, only 20% of individuals within the Backrooms will encounter '''Phenomenon 42''', with the majority never experiencing it. However, in recent years, the cases of '''Phenomenon 42''' encounters have become more frequent, with some experiencing the phenomenon more than twice in their lifetimes. At this moment, the source of the rising number of encounters is unclear.
</font>
{{Underline|ADD8E6}}
{{Underline|ADD8E6}}







<center><font size=5><span style="color: #008080; text-shadow: 0px 0px 5px #003153">Or at least what should have been.</span></font></center>



<center><font size=5><span style="color: #008080; text-shadow: 0px 0px 5px #003153">Instead, it functioned as the beginning of an eye-opening experience, where I was able to get closure on major life events.</span></font></center>



<center><font size=5><span style="color: #008080; text-shadow: 0px 0px 5px #003153">It all started when an accidental noclip brought me to [[Level 188.8]], which usually would have triggered a freakout due to the abundance of water. In fact, the first few minutes of my stay kept me constantly on edge.</span></font></center>



<center><font size=5><span style="color: #008080; text-shadow: 0px 0px 5px #003153">Though, as time progressed, I felt the urge to jump into the water, despite the everlasting threat of the Hydrolitis Plague, which I had to continually resist.</span></font></center>



<center><font size=5><span style="color: #008080; text-shadow: 0px 0px 5px #003153">Things came to a head as I noclipped out of the level to Level 37, which resumed the urge.</span></font></center>



<center><font size=5><span style="color: #008080; text-shadow: 0px 0px 5px #003153">A part of me wanted to jump, but another, deep down in my heart, still bounded by my everlasting fear, resisted me.</span></font></center>



<center><font size=5><span style="color: #008080; text-shadow: 0px 0px 5px #003153">Despite the attempts to resist, I completely ignored my fight or flight response and dove straight in.</span></font></center>



<center><font size=5><span style="color: #008080; text-shadow: 0px 0px 5px #003153">The water felt refreshing all around me, and even though my body told me to get out from years of training, I wanted more.</span></font></center>



<center><font size=5><span style="color: #008080; text-shadow: 0px 0px 5px #003153">Aquatic levels, where I once avoided, became my new favorite levels. I constantly spent long periods of time within hot tubs and pools, and my fear slowly dwindled little by little.</span></font></center>



<center><font size=5><span style="color: #008080; text-shadow: 0px 0px 5px #003153">So, as I opened the unlocked door in [[Level 1]], usually leading to [[Level 2]], only to be greeted by a massive expanse of water, I did not run away from it, instead I accepted it, seemingly knowing that it was good.</span></font></center>



<center><font size=5><span style="color: #008080; text-shadow: 0px 0px 5px #003153">As I floated within the water, it pulled me in deeper, eventually putting me into a trance like state. All my senses were muted, except for sight and smell. Despite being surrounded by water, I was able to breathe normally.</span></font></center>



<center><font size=5><span style="color: #008080; text-shadow: 0px 0px 5px #003153">Eventually, my life began to play out similar to a movie. I saw the typical staples of my life: the fun I missed out on, the relentless bullying, the moment I entered the Backrooms, my first time encountering an entity, and the friends I met along the way. The typical stuff.</span></font></center>



<center><font size=5><span style="color: #008080; text-shadow: 0px 0px 5px #003153">One thing I did not expect to get, was the experience that gave me the everlasting fear of water.</span></font></center>



<center><font size=5><span style="color: #008080; text-shadow: 0px 0px 5px #003153">I never remembered how or what happened to make me so afraid of water. I always thought that I was born that way.</span></font></center>



<center><font size=5><span style="color: #008080; text-shadow: 0px 0px 5px #003153">However that was not the case.</span></font></center>



<center><font size=5><span style="color: #008080; text-shadow: 0px 0px 5px #003153">I was present in a large fishing boat. A shoreline was visible to my left, though only expansive ocean was visible to my right, The tide around me was choppy. The sky above me was sunny, with no clouds to be seen. On the boat were five other people: my mom, my dad, and three other girls, one of which I recognized instantly.</span></font></center>



<center><font size=5><span style="color: #008080; text-shadow: 0px 0px 5px #003153">My older sister.</span></font></center>



<center><font size=5><span style="color: #008080; text-shadow: 0px 0px 5px #003153">Now, I always knew I had an older sister, she was the emergency adult whether mom or dad would go away. Her face would be etched into the back of my mind. She died when I was six years old, but I never figured out how.</span></font></center>



<center><font size=5><span style="color: #008080; text-shadow: 0px 0px 5px #003153">I recognized the two girls accompanying my sister within the boat as her friends, who she would invite over while babysitting me. They were not too close to her, since she officially met them 2 months before the current moment within my memories. They did not like me, with them constantly saying that I was an "ugly baby".</span></font></center>



<center><font size=5><span style="color: #008080; text-shadow: 0px 0px 5px #003153">The boating trip was pitched as a family trip, a way for my sister to get to know her new friends more, and for my parents to have a little break away from home. Since they could not find a nanny to babysit me, I came along.</span></font></center>



<center><font size=5><span style="color: #008080; text-shadow: 0px 0px 5px #003153">That was their biggest mistake, as they would end up scarring me forever.</span></font></center>



<center><font size=5><span style="color: #008080; text-shadow: 0px 0px 5px #003153">About an hour into the trip, my sister's friends decided to play a "prank" on her, by pushing her into the water. As my sister was looking over the edge of the boat, one of the friends went behind her and pushed her in with a shove, and she fell into the water with a splash. Even though they knew she was not able to swim, they still assumed that the life vest she had on would keep her afloat until she was rescued out of the water.</span></font></center>



<center><font size=5><span style="color: #008080; text-shadow: 0px 0px 5px #003153">However, they were very, very wrong, as the life vest was not inflated properly. I watched as my sister struggled against the waves, before going under. Her "friends" suddenly realized she was gone, and they were mortified. They ran to my parents for help, and my dad offered to try and save her. He jumped in the water after her.</span></font></center>



<center><font size=5><span style="color: #008080; text-shadow: 0px 0px 5px #003153">My parents rushed me into a side room, but I crawled and watched through an adjacent window. Out of that one window, I watched on, and 10 minutes later, I saw my dad reemerge out of the water, with my sister's unconscious body. Despite our attempts at resuscitation, she did not wake up.</span></font></center>



<center><font size=5><span style="color: #008080; text-shadow: 0px 0px 5px #003153">Even as she was rushed to the hospital, the doctors stated the one thing that we did not want to hear: she was dead. Immediately, the friends ran out of the room, crying. I saw my parents crying, and so did I.</span></font></center>



<center><font size=5><span style="color: #008080; text-shadow: 0px 0px 5px #003153">From then on, I developed a fear of water, assuming that the water was going to kill me, just like what happened to my sister.</span></font></center>



<center><font size=5><span style="color: #008080; text-shadow: 0px 0px 5px #003153">They say the brain gets rid of traumatic memories if it is too hard for one to cope with, and I believe that was what happened to me, hence why I did not remember what happened on that day.</span></font></center>



<center><font size=5><span style="color: #008080; text-shadow: 0px 0px 5px #003153">After the movie of my memories ended, I felt a strong pull, and I woke up in [[Level 399]], specifically within the Neon Natatorium.</span></font></center>



<center><font size=5><span style="color: #008080; text-shadow: 0px 0px 5px #003153">Now, even though I still express mild apprehension when I see water, old habits die hard after all, I am no longer deeply scared of water, and I am not afraid to pass through aquatic levels as my journey progresses. I have finally gotten closure on my life, and I know I made my older sister proud.</span></font></center>



<center><font size=5><span style="color: #008080; text-shadow: 0px 0px 5px #003153">I believe the Backrooms finally allowed me mercy from its constant trials and tribulations, while also giving me an opportunity to overcome my deepest fear.</span></font></center>



<center><font size=5><span style="color: #008080; text-shadow: 0px 0px 5px #003153">And for that I say...</span></font></center>



<center><font size=5><span style="color: #008080; text-shadow: 0px 0px 5px #003153">...thank you.</span></font></center>
